          "body": "The opening three verses are unprecedented in their concreteness: David does not merely ask for God's help but asks Him to take up specific weapons — buckler, shield, spear, battle-axe (vv. 2-3). The request is grounded in the covenant tradition of Yahweh as Divine Warrior (Exodus 15:3; Isaiah 42:13; Deuteronomy 32:41-43), the God who goes before His people in battle. But the most intimate moment in the opening is v. 3b: 'Say to my soul, I am your salvation.' Before any enemy is routed, before any net is sprung back, David asks God to speak directly to his inner person — nephesh — and identify Himself as yeshuah. The word of God to the soul precedes the action of God in history. This is the psalm's pastoral center: the prayer for divine intervention is anchored in divine speech — God's own self-identification as Savior is the ground on which all the subsequent petitions stand."
