          "body": "Verses 9-10 are the psalm's first doxological peak. After the imprecations, the psalm pivots sharply: 'my soul shall rejoice in the Lord; it shall exult in His salvation.' The verb rejoice (gil) is a strong, embodied term — leaping, spinning with joy. David pledges this before deliverance comes. Then in verse 10 the doxology becomes anatomical: 'all my bones will say, Lord, who is like You?' Every part of the body — not just the lips — will participate in the praise. The rhetorical question 'who is like You?' (*mi kamokha*) is the Exodus doxology (Exodus 15:11) repurposed for personal crisis. The same God who split the sea for the nation will deliver the individual from those 'too strong for him.' The phrase 'too strong for him' is the theological key: the afflicted cannot win this fight; the enemy is beyond his capacity. That is precisely why the Divine Warrior of vv. 1-3 is necessary. God's incomparability is most visible when the gap between the powerful enemy and the powerless sufferer is widest."
